values.comments:
This course examines how we as consumers in the "Western" world engage with musical difference largely through the products of the global entertainment industry. The course examines music cultures in contact in a variety of ways-- particularly as traditions in transformation. Students gain an understanding of traditional music as live, meaningful person-to-person music making, by examining the music in its original site of production, and then considering its transformation once it is removed, and recontextualized in a variety of ways. The purpose of the course is to enable students to become informed and critical consumers of "World Music" by telling a series of stories about particular recordings made with, or using the music of, peoples culturally and geographically distant from the US. Students come to understand that not all music downloads containing music from unfamiliar places are the same, and that particular recordings may be embedded in intriguing and controversial narratives of production and consumption. At the very least, students should emerge from the class with a clear understanding that the production, distribution, and consumption of world music is rarely a neutral process. &#8232;&#8232;

Students found this course to be “interesting and fun.” Most students felt that the musical approach to this course “stimulates interest, the sharing of ideas, and debate.” Students felt like they learned a lot about content that they had never come across in other courses. One student wrote, “The class definitely provided me with new perspectives that will be useful in my other work.” Students praised the incorporation of multimedia, like music videos, as a way to thoroughly explore the material.&#8232;&#8232;

The students praised Professor Rothchild for her “use of non-traditional methods of teaching,” such as her use of “mind maps” rather than typical lecture outlines. Students wrote that she was “very knowledgeable” and that she “was able to engage students and allowed them to participate many times in lecture.” Students also agreed that Professor Rothchild was very accessible and eager to answer the questions of her students. &#8232;

&#8232;Students thought that the workload for this class was very fair and reasonably light. They recommended this course to other students interested in the topic. This class fulfills three General Requirements: Arts & Letters, Cross Cultural Analysis, and Cultural Diversity in U.S. This course is open to Freshmen and Upperclassmen and it has no prerequisites.
